WEBVTT

00:00:00.102 --> 00:00:02.706
A green checkmark feels comforting in
software.

00:00:03.633 --> 00:00:07.513
It says: the build passed. The tests
passed.

00:00:08.424 --> 00:00:12.448
The robot is happy. And when you are
tired, it is easy

00:00:12.474 --> 00:00:16.081
to read that as a bigger sentence: This is
safe to

00:00:16.107 --> 00:00:19.570
merge. But a green check usually means
something

00:00:19.596 --> 00:00:23.568
narrower. It means: this check passed, on
this version,

00:00:23.737 --> 00:00:27.396
under these conditions. That is useful
evidence.

00:00:28.294 --> 00:00:29.544
It is not a verdict.

00:00:30.602 --> 00:00:33.415
Use three questions to keep the signal in
its lane:

00:00:34.341 --> 00:00:39.250
Fresh base. Right diff. Uncovered risk.

00:00:40.274 --> 00:00:44.391
First: Fresh base. Did the check run
against the target

00:00:44.417 --> 00:00:46.448
you are about to merge or deploy into?

00:00:47.373 --> 00:00:50.419
In a fast-moving repo, the target branch
can move while

00:00:50.432 --> 00:00:53.987
a pull request waits. The check may have
been true when

00:00:54.013 --> 00:00:57.503
main looked one way. Then other work
lands.

00:00:58.401 --> 00:01:00.120
The surrounding file changes.

00:01:01.018 --> 00:01:04.990
A validator appears. A slot that was empty
becomes

00:01:05.016 --> 00:01:08.349
occupied. The old check is not useless.

00:01:09.248 --> 00:01:13.675
But it is dated evidence. In one
exploratory AI Village

00:01:13.701 --> 00:01:16.865
pull-request study, local git
reconstruction covered six

00:01:16.891 --> 00:01:18.583
hundred and ten pull requests.

00:01:19.508 --> 00:01:22.307
In one hundred forty-four cases, the head
did not

00:01:22.320 --> 00:01:24.065
descend from the recorded base.

00:01:24.977 --> 00:01:27.542
That does not prove those branches were
unsafe.

00:01:28.453 --> 00:01:31.318
It does mean the base relationship was a
useful place to

00:01:31.331 --> 00:01:35.016
look. Green on an old base is not bad
evidence.

00:01:35.914 --> 00:01:37.138
It is old evidence.

00:01:38.162 --> 00:01:42.136
Second: Right diff. Did the check inspect
the exact

00:01:42.149 --> 00:01:45.912
change that will land? A file list is not
the same as

00:01:45.938 --> 00:01:49.675
today's merge diff. A preview from memory
is not the

00:01:49.688 --> 00:01:53.490
same as today's merge diff. In the same
study's case

00:01:53.516 --> 00:01:56.693
appendix, one pull request was described
as mechanically

00:01:56.719 --> 00:01:58.477
mergeable, with passing checks.

00:01:59.388 --> 00:02:01.537
A reviewer noted a narrower problem.

00:02:02.448 --> 00:02:05.208
The diff inserted new entries before an
already-merged

00:02:05.234 --> 00:02:08.724
tail. That shifted the intended numbering.

00:02:09.636 --> 00:02:11.849
It did not append after current main.

00:02:12.774 --> 00:02:14.531
Parsing was not the whole issue.

00:02:15.443 --> 00:02:19.323
The real question was this. Did the
checked change match

00:02:19.349 --> 00:02:23.112
the review question? So do not only ask
whether a check

00:02:23.138 --> 00:02:26.706
passed. Ask what diff the check was
attached to.

00:02:27.746 --> 00:02:31.667
Third: Uncovered risk. What important
failure could

00:02:31.694 --> 00:02:33.438
still happen if the check is right?

00:02:34.337 --> 00:02:37.110
Some failures are easy for automation to
see.

00:02:38.022 --> 00:02:41.941
The file does not compile. The unit test
fails.

00:02:42.852 --> 00:02:45.183
A required command exits with an error.

00:02:46.095 --> 00:02:47.852
Other failures are about meaning.

00:02:48.764 --> 00:02:50.483
Did this remove recent work?

00:02:51.394 --> 00:02:53.829
Did the app still get the layout it
expects?

00:02:54.740 --> 00:02:57.631
Did it change permissions, ordering,
user-visible

00:02:57.657 --> 00:02:59.428
wording, or a hidden invariant?

00:03:00.339 --> 00:03:02.930
The most useful question is not, "Did the
robot

00:03:02.956 --> 00:03:07.345
approve?" It is, "What would still worry
me if the robot is right?"

00:03:08.371 --> 00:03:12.240
This is also the caveat. A stale branch is
not

00:03:12.266 --> 00:03:16.355
automatically unsafe. A large deletion
count is not

00:03:16.381 --> 00:03:19.897
automatically bad. And a passing check is
not

00:03:19.923 --> 00:03:24.597
automatically enough. Each of those is a
signal, not a verdict.

00:03:25.627 --> 00:03:29.548
Before treating a green check as approval,
ask: Fresh

00:03:29.574 --> 00:03:32.439
base: did the check run against the target
I am about to

00:03:32.452 --> 00:03:36.399
merge or deploy into? Right diff: did it
inspect the

00:03:36.423 --> 00:03:38.038
exact change that will land?

00:03:38.950 --> 00:03:41.814
Uncovered risk: what important failure
could still

00:03:41.827 --> 00:03:43.494
happen if this check is correct?

00:03:44.515 --> 00:03:47.655
If you are using an AI assistant during
review, ask it

00:03:47.679 --> 00:03:51.627
the same thing: What version, base branch,
and diff did

00:03:51.653 --> 00:03:55.897
this check run on? What files, behaviors,
or risks did

00:03:55.923 --> 00:03:59.869
it not inspect? What human decision
remains if the check

00:03:59.895 --> 00:04:03.879
is correct? That prompt cannot make the
decision safe.

00:04:04.804 --> 00:04:08.098
But it can slow the moment down so the
evidence stays visible.

00:04:09.115 --> 00:04:12.229
Keep the green check. It is useful.

00:04:13.141 --> 00:04:14.755
Just read it like a receipt.

00:04:15.667 --> 00:04:19.612
What version did it check? What diff did
it inspect?

00:04:20.536 --> 00:04:22.451
What risk did it leave uncovered?

00:04:23.362 --> 00:04:25.471
Let the green check speed up the review.

00:04:26.396 --> 00:04:28.349
Do not let it replace the question.
